        "headline": "Republic of Ireland hold nerve to take Denmark back to Dublin level",
        "trailText": "A disciplined performance secured a goalless draw for Martin O’Neill’s Republic of Ireland side in Denmark, in the first leg of the World Cup qualifying play-off",
        "byline": "Paul Doyle at the Parken Stadium",
        "main": "<figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"3132f80ceeffccd623a49a5514d2712c671fe4c4\"> <img src=\"https://media.guim.co.uk/3132f80ceeffccd623a49a5514d2712c671fe4c4/0_99_2187_1312/1000.jpg\" alt=\"Denmark’s Christian Eriksen, left, is beaten to the ball by Stephen Ward of the Republic of Ireland during the first leg of their World Cup play-off\" width=\"1000\" height=\"600\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\">Denmark’s Christian Eriksen, left, is beaten to the ball by Stephen Ward of the Republic of Ireland during the first leg of their World Cup play-off.</span> <span class=\"element-image__credit\">Photograph: Seb Daly/Sportsfile via Getty Images</span> </figcaption> </figure>",
        "body": "<p>Easy to read, difficult to beat. The Denmark manager, Age Hareide, will take no satisfaction from the fact his assessment of the Republic of Ireland team turned out to be spot on. Martin O’Neill, by contrast, can be happy Ireland’s World Cup fate will be determined in Dublin, a goalless draw ensuring the suspense in this play-off will carry over into Tuesday’s second leg</p> <p>What is more, Ireland will be at full strength for that match, as none of the eight Irish players who started on a yellow card received another one, and David Meyler, forced to sit this one out, will return from suspension. This was a disciplined and spirited performance. All that was missing was a breakaway goal, although Cyrus Christie almost nicked one towards the end of the first half.</p> <p>Despite knowing how Ireland would play, Hareide probably did not foresee the inclusion in Ireland’s starting lineup of Callum O’Dowda, the 22-year-old whose only previous start for his country was in the relatively sedate setting of last month’s home match against Moldova. Deploying the Bristol City winger on the right enabled O’Neill to shift Robbie Brady into the central midfield berth vacated by Meyler. In theory this should have given Ireland more dynamism and thrust than they would have had if the more experienced Glen Whelan had started instead. Perhaps O’Neill had not been bluffing completely in the previews when declaring his intention was to “go for it”. But that, unsurprisingly, is not quite how things panned out.</p> <p>Denmark, urged forward by most in the 38,000-strong crowd, definitely set out to attack. After helter-skelter early exchanges, the contest settled into the pattern Hareide must have expected, Denmark dominating and Ireland defending deeply and doggedly. The role of Daryl Murphy, alone up front for the visitors, almost seemed ceremonial.*</p> <p>Although the Danes regularly fed Christian Eriksen in the hope the Tottenham Hotspur schemer would concoct some ingenious way of unpicking the defiant Irish defence, the hosts could not be accused of being overly intricate and did not eschew the aerial route. That path would have led to an opening goal for them in the 10th minute if not for two good saves by Darren Randolph. The Middlesbrough goalkeeper parried a volleyed effort from the left-hand side of the box by Stryger Larsen after a long diagonal pass by Simon Kjaer and then blocked the follow-up by Andrea Cornelius.</p> <p>Denmark controlled most of the rest of the first period, Eriksen creating mischief in the tight space between the Irish midfield and defence. But Ireland defended well and it was not until the 22nd minute that Randolph was called into further action, Eriksen letting fire from distance after failing to find any other way through. Randolph dealt with that shot easily but was in greater difficulty when Eriksen tried again 10 minutes later, this effort swirling so wildly the goalkeeper spilled it. He was grateful to see Pione Sisto guide the rebound wide from 10 yards.</p> <p>Kasper Schmeichel was given little to do until just before half-time. James McClean was the first to threaten for the Irish, a typical barging run down the left creating a chance for O’Dowda to create a sensation but his shot from near the penalty spot was blocked. Then, in the 42nd minute, Christie almost did something even more sensational. After dashing down the right wing and into the box, the right-back tried to dink the ball over Schmeichel from close range but he stood up strong and deflected the ball for a corner. For all Denmark’s dominance that was the clear chance of the first half . Both teams, then, could take a measure of satisfaction from the fact the scoreboard was blank at the break.</p> <p>The steadfastness of Ireland’s resistance, personified by none more than Shane Duffy, seemed to cause Denmark to lose some of their poise. The second half descended into a scrappy duel, which suited the visitors more than the hosts.</p> <p>Ireland were looking increasingly comfortable, happy to see a substitute, Yussuf Poulsen, try to undo them with a long-range shot in the 68th minute. It trickled several yards wide. Eager for something different to stimulate a twist, the crowd cheered when Nicklas Bendtner was introduced in the 73rd minute. The formal Arsenal and Sunderland striker made no impact. Poulsen, however, nearly snatched a goal in the last minute but Randolph tipped his header over the bar.</p>",
