        "headline": "Rise of One Nation thickens the plot in Queensland election",
        "standfirst": "<p>Recent polling suggests the party will make a big impact, but the number of seats it could win hinges on a broad mix of factors</p>",
        "trailText": "Recent polling suggests the party will make a big impact, but the number of seats it could win hinges on a broad mix of factors",
        "byline": "Ben Raue",
        "main": "<figure class=\"element element-image element--showcase\" data-media-id=\"817515a31e3a301ec6f9a9100a4a85f92f87553c\"> <img src=\"https://media.guim.co.uk/817515a31e3a301ec6f9a9100a4a85f92f87553c/0_0_5568_3712/1000.jpg\" alt=\"Pauline Hanson speaks to Queenslanders\" width=\"1000\" height=\"667\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\">Pauline Hanson addresses locals during a stop on the One Nation ‘Battler Bus’ tour in Gladstone, Queensland this month. </span> <span class=\"element-image__credit\">Photograph: Dave Hunt/AAP</span> </figcaption> </figure>",
        "body": "<p>Pauline Hanson’s One Nation party has burst back on to the Australian political scene after last year’s federal election, when it won four Senate seats, and has surged in the polls since then. Recent polling suggests it will make a big impact in this month’s Queensland state election.<br /></p> <p>Seven polls since May 2017 have shown One Nation’s vote between 15% and 18%, and last week’s Galaxy poll put the party on 18%. Two polls at the beginning of this year predicted a vote of more than 20%.</p> <p>A vote of 18% would be quite high for a minor party, but our electoral system does not neatly translate votes into seats. There are a lot of factors that will influence how many seats One Nation could win if its vote is as high as polls suggest.</p> <aside class=\"element element-rich-link element--thumbnail\"> <p> <span>Related: </span><a href=\"https://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/2017/nov/10/sex-shop-shock-leaves-pauline-hanson-squirming\">Sex shop shock leaves Pauline Hanson squirming</a> </p> </aside>  <p>One Nation’s first electoral test came in the 1998 Queensland election, as a prelude to the federal election that year. The party polled 22.7% of the vote, overtaking the separate Liberal and National parties to come second. The two Coalition parties collectively polled 31%, while Labor managed almost 39%.</p> <p>With this vote, One Nation came in the top two in 33 out of 89 state electorates, but managed to win only in 11.</p> <p>It tended to do well in regional areas, but not so well in Brisbane. Its strongest areas encompassed all the seats in the Ipswich area, as well as large rural electorates up the coast and further inland. It also did quite well in smaller coastal towns, but not in Cairns and Townsville.</p> <p>It won seats off Labor and the Nationals. The party’s candidates defeated six MPs of Labor and five from the National party. Of the 33 seats where it came in the top two, 20 of those contests were against Labor. This showed Labor had polled much higher than the conservative parties.</p>  <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"51e4ff339a8920cd74ac4a86ef9fe66b5708a3bd\"> <img src=\"https://media.guim.co.uk/51e4ff339a8920cd74ac4a86ef9fe66b5708a3bd/0_139_4419_2652/1000.jpg\" alt=\"Pauline Hanson  and One Nation candidate for Bowen Sam Cox\" width=\"1000\" height=\"600\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\">Pauline Hanson and One Nation candidate for Bowen Sam Cox walk past the Big Mango in Bowen on Friday.</span> <span class=\"element-image__credit\">Photograph: Dave Hunt/AAP</span> </figcaption> </figure>  <p>A lot has changed since 1998. The former Coalition parties have merged, the voting system has changed, and One Nation, which was dormant for more than a decade, is a lot more active now.</p> <p>We can’t use recent state election results to judge where One Nation might perform best – the party ran only 11 candidates at the last state election, and polled less than 1% of the vote. But it did manage more than 9% of the statewide vote in the Senate at last year’s federal election. This data has been broken down at the state electoral level <a href=\"https://abjago.net/4PP-QLD-projections-from-senate-results\">by Alex Jago</a>, and gives us a sense of the places where One Nation would be expected to do best.</p> <aside class=\"element element-rich-link element--thumbnail\"> <p> <span>Related: </span><a href=\"https://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/2017/oct/12/one-nation-queensland-preference-plan-designed-to-do-labor-over\">One Nation Queensland preference plan 'designed to do Labor over'</a> </p> </aside>  <p>The pattern is similar to what we saw in 1998: urban fringe, small regional towns and large rural electorates, on the coast and inland. The party’s vote was highest in the Ipswich fringe seat of Lockyer, where Hanson came close to victory at the 2015 state election. One Nation does slightly better in Liberal National party seats, but is still a threat in several Labor seats in places such as Townsville and Ipswich.</p> <p>If One Nation polls as high as 18%, it will come in the top two, on primary votes, in many seats – but that won’t be enough to win seats. In most places, the party will not be in a position to win on primary votes, and will require preferences from other candidates.</p> <p>The preference system has changed since the last election – voters will now be required to number every box. This means more preferences will play a role in deciding the result. It will also make it easier for a candidate in second place to catch up on a rival.</p> <p>Labor and the Greens have declared they will not give preferences to One Nation. The LNP plans to give preferences to One Nation over Labor in at least 50 seats (out of the 61 seats where One Nation is standing). Katter’s Australian party may poll a substantial number of votes in some north Queensland seats, and those may be crucial in a seat’s result.</p> <aside class=\"element element-rich-link element--thumbnail\"> <p> <span>Related: </span><a href=\"https://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/2017/oct/30/queensland-election-lnp-leader-targets-disenchanted-in-one-nation-heartland\">Queensland election: LNP leader targets 'disenchanted' One Nation voters</a> </p> </aside>  <p>While parties recommend preferences, their voters are free to reject that recommendation – many Labor voters chose to preference One Nation in 2016, despite Labor’s preference recommendation suggesting otherwise.</p> <p> One Nation will struggle to secure seats off the LNP without Labor and Greens preferences – so it would probably need a primary vote lead to win such a contest. Where the party is competing with Labor, LNP preferences will play a big role in deciding the result – and One Nation’s prospects have been improved by Friday’s announcement that the LNP will give them preferences in most of their contests.</p> <p>The rise of One Nation will generally increase the complexity and unpredictability in this election. A more fragmented political system will result in candidates being elected with fewer primary votes, relying more on preferences. If One Nation can win a handful of seats, it will also increase the chance of a hung parliament.</p> <p>It is possible One Nation will not be able to keep up its current levels of polling. The party suffered under the pressure of an election campaign in Western Australia this year, and ended up polling about 8% in the upper house, comparedwith well over 10% earlier in the campaign. A drop of even a few percentage points would make it much harder forit to win seats.</p>",
